01:21:58.080 --> 01:22:10.319
John Ellis: It's like, it's basic, it's not that advanced, but it often gets the job done, and then when it's ready, it has an end-thinking token, and then begins to respond. That's a reasoning model. Most models nowadays actually can do both.

366
01:22:10.670 --> 01:22:18.469
John Ellis: You can interact with it. It used to be you had to choose the model that was the reasoning model versus the non-reasoning. Now, many models can flexibly go between the two.

367
01:22:18.670 --> 01:22:27.199
John Ellis: And based on what you're asking, if it has not much of an idea of how to respond, it'll enter into thinking mode first. All that's happening is…

368
01:22:27.720 --> 01:22:31.999
John Ellis: It's taking what it thought, And putting it into context.

369
01:22:32.880 --> 01:22:37.110
John Ellis: So a lot of this is about getting better and better context.

370
01:22:37.760 --> 01:22:43.170
John Ellis: And it turns out this is the way to understand not only reasoning models, but even agents as well.

371
01:22:43.440 --> 01:22:50.750
John Ellis: It's all about putting into context that crucial information that, when applied to attention.

372
01:22:51.030 --> 01:22:53.239
John Ellis: Can actually do the thing that you need it to do.

373
01:22:55.400 --> 01:22:56.690
John Ellis: Let's talk about tools.

